# Scientific Writing Guidelines for GIS Research Papers

## 1  Purpose
Provide a shared, discipline‑appropriate framework that ensures consistency, clarity, and academic rigour across all manuscripts produced by our group.

## 2  Target Audience
Master’s and PhD students, research assistants, and staff collaborating on Geographic Information Science (GIS) research at TU Delft.

---

## 3  Document Structure (IMRaD‑plus)
| Section | Key Points | Typical Length |
|---------|------------|----------------|
| **Title Page** | Informative title (≤ 15 words), author list with ORCID IDs, institutional affiliation, word count | 1 page |
| **Abstract** | Structured (Background, Methods, Results, Conclusions), ≤ 250 words, 3–6 keywords | ½ page |
| **1 Introduction** | Context ➜ Gap ➜ Aim ➜ Overview of paper | ~15 % |
| **2 Methods** | Study area, data sources, preprocessing, algorithms, software (incl. version), CRS, statistical tests; written in past tense | ~25 % |
| **3 Results** | Present findings without interpretation; include tables, figures, statistics | ~25 % |
| **4 Discussion** | Interpret findings, compare with literature, limitations, implications | ~20 % |
| **5 Conclusion** | Concise answers to research questions + future work | ~5 % |
| **Acknowledgements** | Funding (grant #), data providers, contributions | – |
| **References** | APA 7th or journal‑specified style (use Zotero/Mendeley); all DOIs hyperlinked | – |
| **Appendices / Supplementary** | Extended tables, code, large maps | – |

